

Here are ten SQL queries that demonstrate the use of various DML statements, operators, and functions:

1>
Insert a new record into the "students" table:
______________________________________________________________
INSERT INTO students (id, name, age, grade) VALUES (1, 'Alice', 18, 'A');

2>
Select all records from the "students" table:
___________________________________________________________________
SELECT * FROM students;

3>
Update the grade of a student:
____________________________________________________
UPDATE students SET grade = 'B' WHERE id = 1;

4>
Delete a record from the "students" table:
________________________________________________
DELETE FROM students WHERE id = 1;

5>
Select the total number of students in each grade:
______________________________________________
SELECT grade, COUNT(*) AS total_students FROM students GROUP BY grade;

6>
Select the average age of students:
_____________________________________________
SELECT AVG(age) AS average_age FROM students;

7>
Select the name of students whose name starts with 'A':
________________________________________________
SELECT name FROM students WHERE name LIKE 'A%';

8>
Select the current date and time:
_________________________________________
SELECT NOW() AS current_datetime;

9>
Select the total number of students:
__________________________________________
SELECT COUNT(*) AS total_students FROM students;

10>
Select the maximum and minimum age of students:
____________________________________
SELECT MAX(age) AS max_age, MIN(age) AS min_age FROM students;
